  "prompt_text": "Prove by induction that the sum of the first n natural numbers is n(n+1)/2.",
  "response_text": "To prove by induction that the sum of the first \\(n\\) natural numbers is \\(\\frac{n(n+1)}{2}\\), we will follow these steps:\n\n1. **Base Case**: Verify the statement for \\(n = 1\\).\n2. **Inductive Step**: Assume the statement is true for some arbitrary positive integer \\(k\\), and then prove it for \\(k + 1\\).\n\n### Base Case\n\nFor \\(n = 1\\):\nThe sum of the first 1 natural number is \\(1\\).\nAccording to the formula, \\(\\frac{1(1+1)}{2} = \\frac{2}{2} = 1\\).\nThus, the base case holds.\n\n### Inductive Step\n\nAssume the statement is true for \\(n = k\\). That is, assume:\n\\[1 + 2 + 3 + \\cdots + k = \\frac{k(k+1)}{2}\\]\n\nWe need to show that the statement is also true for \\(n = k + 1\\). That is, we need to prove:\n\\[1 + 2 + 3 + \\cdots + k + (k + 1) = \\frac{(k+1)(k+2)}{2}\\]\n\nStarting from the inductive hypothesis:\n\\[1 + 2 + 3 + \\cdots + k = \\frac{k(k+1)}{2}\\]\n\nAdding \\((k + 1)\\) to both sides:\n\\[\\frac{k(k+1)}{2} + (k + 1) = \\frac{(k+1)(k+2)}{2}\\]\n\nSimplify the left side:\n\\[\\frac{k(k+1)}{2} + \\frac{2(k+1)}{2} = \\frac{k(k+1) + 2(k+1)}{2} = \\frac{(k+1)(k + 2)}{2}\\]\n\nThis matches the right side of what we wanted to prove. Therefore, the statement is true for \\(n = k + 1\\).\n\nBy the principle of mathematical induction, the sum of the first \\(n\\) natural numbers is \\(\\frac{n(n+1)}{2}\\) for all positive integers \\(n\\).\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 6\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
